[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] It’s been available across browsers since March 2019.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] The **`AbortController`** interface represents a controller object that allows you to abort one or more Web requests as and when desired.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] You can create a new `AbortController` object using the `AbortController()` constructor.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] Communicating with an asynchronous operation is done using an `AbortSignal` object.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] Creates a new `AbortController` object instance.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] Returns an `AbortSignal` object instance, which can be used to communicate with, or to abort, an asynchronous operation.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] Aborts an asynchronous operation before it has completed.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] This is able to abort fetch requests, consumption of any response bodies, and streams.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] See the `AbortSignal` page for usage examples.
[src:fetch-api/abortcontroller] You can find a full working example on GitHub; you can also see it running live.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Ajax is not a technology, but rather a programming pattern.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] HTML and CSS can be used in combination to mark up and style information.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The webpage can be modified by JavaScript to dynamically display (and allow the user to interact with) the new information.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The built-in XMLHttpRequest object is used to execute Ajax on webpages, allowing websites to load content onto the screen without refreshing the page.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] In the early-to-mid 1990s, most websites were based on complete HTML pages.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Each user action required a complete new page to be loaded from the server.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] This process was inefficient, as reflected by the user experience: all page content disappeared, then the new page appeared.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Each time the browser reloaded a page because of a partial change, all the content had to be re-sent, even though only some of the information had changed.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] This placed additional load on the server and made bandwidth a limiting factor in performance.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The foundations of AJAX originate back in 1996 with the introduction of JavaScript 1.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Developers quickly discovered that any HTML element which accepted a "src" attribute could be used to fetch remote data.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] By changing the src of a hidden frame, a developer could fetch remote data, process or display it without a page refresh.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The remote data could be a string, JavaScript code, XML or a partial HTML page generated on the server.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The same could be done with `<img>` and `<embed>` tags, but many developers were alarmed at the concept of an executable GIF and preferred to use the hidden `<iframe>`.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] This technique was used for both Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer, the two main browsers at the time, until developers discovered the XMLHTTP server object (MSXML 1.0) was included in Internet Explorer 4.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Browser detection was then used to either implement the hidden `<iframe>` in Netscape or use the XMLHTTP (MSXML 1.0) object in IE 4.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] In 1996, the iframe tag was introduced by Internet Explorer; like the object element, it can load a part of the web page asynchronously.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] In 1998, the Microsoft Outlook Web Access team developed the concept behind the XMLHttpRequest scripting object.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] It appeared as XMLHTTP in the second version of the MSXML library, which shipped with Internet Explorer 5.0 in March 1999.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The functionality of the Windows XMLHTTP ActiveX control in IE 5 was later implemented by Mozilla Firefox, Safari, Opera, Google Chrome, and other browsers as the XMLHttpRequest JavaScript object.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Microsoft adopted the native XMLHttpRequest model as of Internet Explorer 7.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Support for the ActiveX version remained in Internet Explorer and on "Internet Explorer mode" in Microsoft Edge.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The utility of these background HTTP requests and asynchronous Web technologies remained fairly obscure until it started appearing in large scale online applications such as Outlook Web Access (2000) and Oddpost (2002).
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Google made a wide deployment of standards-compliant, cross browser Ajax with Gmail (2004) and Google Maps (2005).
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] In October 2004 Kayak.com's public beta release was among the first large-scale e-commerce uses of what their developers at that time called "the xml http thing".
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] This increased interest in Ajax among web program developers.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The term *AJAX* was publicly used on 18 February 2005 by Jesse James Garrett in an article titled *Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications*, based on techniques used on Google pages.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] On 5 April 2006, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) released the first draft specification for the XMLHttpRequest object in an attempt to create an official Web standard.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The latest draft of the XMLHttpRequest object was published on 6 October 2016, and the XMLHttpRequest specification is now a living standard.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] The term *Ajax* has come to represent a broad group of Web technologies that can be used to implement a Web application that communicates with a server in the background, without interfering with the current state of the page.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Since then, however, there have been a number of developments in the technologies used in an Ajax application, and in the definition of the term Ajax itself.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] XML is no longer required for data interchange and, therefore, XSLT is no longer required for the manipulation of data.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is often used as an alternative format for data interchange, although other formats such as preformatted HTML or plain text can also be used.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] A variety of popular JavaScript libraries, including jQuery, include abstractions to assist in executing Ajax requests.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] An example of a simple Ajax request using the GET method, written in JavaScript.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Ajax offers several benefits that can significantly enhance web application performance and user experience.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] By reducing server traffic and improving speed, Ajax plays a crucial role in modern web development.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] One key advantage of Ajax is its capacity to render web applications without requiring data retrieval, resulting in reduced server traffic.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] This optimization minimizes response times on both the server and client sides, eliminating the need for users to endure loading screens.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Furthermore, Ajax facilitates asynchronous processing by simplifying the utilization of XmlHttpRequest, which enables efficient handling of requests for asynchronous data retrieval.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Additionally, the dynamic loading of content enhances the application's performance significantly.
[src:fetch-api/ajax-programming] Besides, Ajax enjoys broad support across all major web browsers, including Microsoft Internet Explorer versions 5 and above, Mozilla Firefox versions 1.0 and beyond, Opera versions 7.6 and above, and Apple Safari versions 1.2 and higher.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API provides an interface for fetching resources (including across the network).
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] It is a more powerful and flexible replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API uses `Request` and `Response` objects (and other things involved with network requests), as well as related concepts such as CORS and the HTTP Origin header semantics.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] For making a request and fetching a resource, use the `fetch()` method.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] It is a global method in both `Window` and `Worker` contexts.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] This makes it available in pretty much any context you might want to fetch resources in.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method takes one mandatory argument, the path to the resource you want to fetch.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] It returns a `Promise` that resolves to the `Response` to that request — as soon as the server responds with headers — **even if the server response is an HTTP error status**.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] You can also optionally pass in an `init` options object as the second argument (see `Request`).
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] Once a `Response` is retrieved, there are a number of methods available to define what the body content is and how it should be handled.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] You can create a request and response directly using the `Request()` and `Response()` constructors, but it's uncommon to do this directly.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] Instead, these are more likely to be created as results of other API actions (for example, `FetchEvent.respondWith()` from service workers).
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] Find out more about using the Fetch API features in Using Fetch.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] The `fetchLater()` API enables a developer to request a *deferred fetch*, that can be sent after a specified period of time, or when the page is closed or navigated away from.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method used to fetch a resource.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] Represents the set of options that can be used to configure a deferred fetch request.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] Represents the result of requesting a deferred fetch.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] Represents response/request headers, allowing you to query them and take different actions depending on the results.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] Controls the top-level quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:fetch-api/api-fetch-api] Controls the shared cross-origin subframe quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] It’s been available across browsers since March 2017.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] The **`Request`** interface of the Fetch API represents a resource request.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] You can create a new `Request` object using the `Request()` constructor, but you are more likely to encounter a `Request` object being returned as the result of another API operation, such as a service worker `FetchEvent.request`.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] A `ReadableStream` of the body contents.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Stores `true` or `false` to indicate whether or not the body has been used in a request yet.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Contains the cache mode of the request (e.g., `default`, `reload`, `no-cache`).
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Contains a value controlling whether credentials should be included with the request (e.g., `omit`, `same-origin`, `include`).
[src:fetch-api/api-request] A string describing the type of content being requested.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] The duplex mode of the request, which determines whether the browser must send the entire request before processing the response.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Contains the associated `Headers` object of the request.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Contains the subresource integrity value of the request (e.g., `sha256-BpfBw7ivV8q2jLiT13fxDYAe2tJllusRSZ273h2nFSE=`).
[src:fetch-api/api-request] A boolean indicating whether the request is a history navigation.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] A boolean indicating whether the request is a user-triggered reload.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Contains the request's `keepalive` setting (`true` or `false`), which indicates whether the browser will keep the associated request alive if the page that initiated it is unloaded before the request is complete.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Contains the mode for how redirects are handled.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] It may be one of `follow`, `error`, or `manual`.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Contains the referrer of the request (e.g., `client`).
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Contains the referrer policy of the request (e.g., `no-referrer`).
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Returns the `AbortSignal` associated with the request.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Returns the request's target address space, which indicates whether it is a loopback, local, or public request.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with an `ArrayBuffer` representation of the request body.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with a `Blob` representation of the request body.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with a `Uint8Array` representation of the request body.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Creates a copy of the current `Request` object.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with a `FormData` representation of the request body.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with the result of parsing the request body as `JSON`.
[src:fetch-api/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with a text representation of the request body.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] The **`Response`** interface of the Fetch API represents the response to a request.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] You can create a new `Response` object using the `Response()` constructor, but you are more likely to encounter a `Response` object being returned as the result of another API operation—for example, a service worker `FetchEvent.respondWith`, or a simple `fetch()`.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Stores a boolean value that declares whether the body has been used in a response yet.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] The `Headers` object associated with the response.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] A boolean indicating whether the response was successful (status in the range `200` – `299`) or not.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Indicates whether or not the response is the result of a redirect (that is, its URL list has more than one entry).
[src:fetch-api/api-response] The status message corresponding to the status code.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] The type of the response (e.g., `basic`, `cors`).
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Returns a new `Response` object associated with a network error.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Returns a new response with a different URL.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Returns a new `Response` object for returning the provided JSON encoded data.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with an `ArrayBuffer` representation of the response body.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with a `Blob` representation of the response body.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with a `Uint8Array` representation of the response body.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with a `FormData` representation of the response body.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with the result of parsing the response body text as `JSON`.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with a text representation of the response body.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] In our basic fetch example (run example live) we use a simple `fetch()` call to grab an image and display it in an `<img>` element.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] The `fetch()` call returns a promise, which resolves to the `Response` object associated with the resource fetch operation.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] You'll notice that since we are requesting an image, we need to run `Response.blob` to give the response its correct MIME type.
[src:fetch-api/api-response] Here we call a PHP program file that generates a JSON string, displaying the result as a JSON value.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The Fetch API provides a JavaScript interface for making HTTP requests and processing the responses.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Fetch is the modern replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`: unlike `XMLHttpRequest`, which uses callbacks, Fetch is promise-based and is integrated with features of the modern web such as service workers and Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS).
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] With the Fetch API, you make a request by calling `fetch()`, which is available as a global function in both `window` and `worker` contexts.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] You pass it a `Request` object or a string containing the URL to fetch, along with an optional argument to configure the request.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function returns a `Promise` which is fulfilled with a `Response` object representing the server's response.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] You can then check the request status and extract the body of the response in various formats, including text and JSON, by calling the appropriate method on the response.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] We declare a string containing the URL and then call `fetch()`, passing the URL with no extra options.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function will reject the promise on some errors, but not if the server responds with an error status like `404`: so we also check the response status and throw if it is not OK.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Otherwise, we fetch the response body content as JSON by calling the `json()` method of `Response`, and log one of its values.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that like `fetch()` itself, `json()` is asynchronous, as are all the other methods to access the response body content.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the rest of this page we'll look in more detail at the different stages of this process.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] 2. optionally, an object containing options to configure the request.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this section we'll look at some of the most commonly-used options.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] To read about all the options that can be given, see the `fetch()` reference page.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then `method` must be one of `GET`, `POST` or `HEAD`.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The request body is the payload of the request: it's the thing the client is sending to the server.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] You cannot include a body with `GET` requests, but it's useful for requests that send content to the server, such as `POST` or `PUT` requests.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, if you want to upload a file to the server, you might make a `POST` request and include the file as the request body.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Other objects are converted to strings using their `toString()` method.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] See Locked and disturbed streams for more information.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request headers give the server information about the request: for example, in a `POST` request, the `Content-Type` header tells the server the format of the request's body.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] To set request headers, assign them to the `headers` option.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Compared to using plain objects, the `Headers` object provides some additional input sanitization.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, it normalizes header names to lowercase, strips leading and trailing whitespace from header values, and prevents certain headers from being set.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Many headers are set automatically by the browser and can't be set by a script: these are called Forbidden request headers.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then the set of permitted headers is further restricted.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] `GET` requests don't have a body, but you can still send data to the server by appending it to the URL as a query string.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common way to send form data to the server.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Whether a request can be made cross-origin or not is determined by the value of the `RequestInit.mode` option.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] This may take one of three values: `cors`, `same-origin`, or `no-cors`.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] See the reference documentation for `RequestInit.mode` for more details.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the context of the Fetch API, a credential is an extra piece of data sent along with the request that the server may use to authenticate the user.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] By default, credentials are only included in same-origin requests.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that if a cookie's `SameSite` attribute is set to `Strict` or `Lax`, then the cookie will not be sent cross-site, even if `credentials` is set to `include`.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Including credentials in cross-origin requests can make a site vulnerable to CSRF attacks, so even if `credentials` is set to `include`, the server must also agree to their inclusion by including the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header in its response.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Additionally, in this situation the server must explicitly specify the client's origin in the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header (that is, `*` is not allowed).
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Request()` constructor takes the same arguments as `fetch()` itself.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] This means that instead of passing options into `fetch()`, you can pass the same options to the `Request()` constructor, and then pass that object to `fetch()`.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] To make a request cancelable, create an `AbortController`, and assign its `AbortSignal` to the request's `signal` property.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] To cancel the request, call the controller's `abort()` method.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` call will reject the promise with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the request is aborted after the `fetch()` call has been fulfilled but before the response body has been read, then attempting to read the response body will reject with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] As soon as the browser has received the response status and headers from the server (and potentially before the response body itself has been received), the promise returned by `fetch()` is fulfilled with a `Response` object.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The promise returned by `fetch()` will reject on some errors, such as a network error or a bad scheme.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] However, if the server responds with an error like `404`, then `fetch()` fulfills with a `Response`, so we have to check the status before we can read the response body.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Response.status` property tells us the numerical status code, and the `Response.ok` property returns `true` if the status is in the 200 range.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Just like the request, the response has a `headers` property which is a `Headers` object, and this contains any response headers that are exposed to scripts, subject to the exclusions made based on the response type.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] These are all asynchronous methods, returning a `Promise` which will be fulfilled with the body content.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The method will throw an exception if the response body is not in the appropriate format: for example, if you call `json()` on a response that can't be parsed as JSON.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request and response bodies are actually `ReadableStream` objects, and whenever you read them, you're streaming the content.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is good for memory efficiency, because the browser doesn't have to buffer the entire response in memory before the caller retrieves it using a method like `json()`.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] This also means that the caller can process the content incrementally as it is received.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] If we use `Response.text()`, as above, we must wait until the whole file has been received before we can process any of it.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this example, we iterate asynchronously over the stream, processing each chunk as it arrives.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that when you access the body directly like this, you get the raw bytes of the response and must transform it yourself.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this case we call `ReadableStream.pipeThrough()` to pipe the response through a `TextDecoderStream`, which decodes the UTF-8-encoded body data as text.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the example below, we fetch a text resource and process it line by line, using a regular expression to look for line endings.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common pattern when implementing an offline cache with service workers.
[src:fetch-api/fetch-api-using-fetch] The service worker wants to return the response to the app, but also to cache the response.
